<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wei, Schneider, Normark &amp; Normark" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Clavaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Clavaspis selvatica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selvatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Clavaspis selvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the Latin adjective meaning wild, literally &quot;of the forest&quot; (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">selva</emphasis>
). Our choice of this name is influenced by the fact that in modern Spanish, the word 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">selva</emphasis>
is identical to its Latin ancestor in form, but now refers specifically to tropical rainforest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
